For, as already intimated, there 18 110 doubt where the Anglo-Saxon Monastery stood, and therefore no doubt where “ the place which used to be called Streneshalc” had its locality, even if the point were not settled by the short Latin extract given a little above. The great “kitchen-midding'' which is known to exist in so many places at the foot of the bank above which slopes the “ Almary Field,'' is quite sufficient as an index to the site of the domestic buildings of the elder monastery3 and, indeed, a very cursory glance at the brae of the said bank, even without the remembrance of the runed Anglo·Saxon comb found there (and now in the local museum), would go very far towards enforcing the same conclusion3 it is full of the matters which go to constitute what is understood by a kitchen-midding.
